1) Overview:
The goal of this project is to determine the factors strongly associated with high medical insurance charges or costs, in order to help reduce costs and risk, and create preventative health programs. 

2) Data Description:
- Source: “Medical Insurance Cost Dataset” - Mosap Abdel-Ghany on Kaggle 
- Rows: 1338
- Features (used fields): Age, Smoker, Region (in the US), Charges

3) Tools Used: 
- Microsoft Excel: Summary descriptive statistics
- MySQL: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA), Querying
- Microsoft Power BI: trends identification, visualizations, DAX measures

4) Data Cleaning:
Data was checked for missing values and validated for incorrect/misspelled values, re-label boolean values.

5) Analysis:
- Data distribution
- Correlation between charges costs vs other factors
- Average charges for smokers
- Ages of beneficiaries with the lowest insurance charges 
- Average charges by smoking status (%)
- Average insurance charges by age group
- Smokers to non-smokers aged above 60 by region (%)

6) Key Insights:
•	Smoking status is the main driver of insurance costs
•	Insurance charges increase with age
•	Individuals in the northeast region incur the lowest charges


